x4freetext: Experiment performed at the HRIBF
tandem accelerator at Oak Ridge National Laboratory
He-4 gas maintained in reaction chamber at a pressure
of 830 mb. 10Be beam entered into reaction chamber
through Havar window with thickness of 5 mu-m. Path
length in He gas was 38 cm. The beam was stopped
after 38 cm in a Mylar absorber with thickness of 46
mu-m (or 144 mu-m for beam energy greater than 38 MeV).
Behind Mylar foil at 0 deg were
three 1cm diameter Si detectors of thicknesses of 100,
150 and 200 mu-m, which formed dE1-dE2-E particle
identification telescope.
Away from the beam axis at 0deg, there were two
arrays of large silicon detectors. These were YY1
wedge-shaped detectors with thickness of 500 mu-m.
The construction of these detectors was such that
eight detectors form a 360deg disk around the beam
axis. In the present case six detectors were formed
into a lamp-shade-type configuration. The inclination
of these detectors from the beam axis was 46deg. The
detectors intercepted angles, measured with respect
to the window, of 13.0 to 43.3deg and 5.0 to 13.5deg,
respectively.
The technique of resonance scattering using a
thick target, developed at the Kurchatov Institute,
was used. It involves the passage of a beam through a
thick target material. As the beam slows down, and
the center-of-mass energy coincides with that of a
resonance of the projectile-target composite system,
a resonant component to the scattering process occurs.
The measurements were performed using a previously
prepared 10Be sample placed in the ion source. The
beam purity was better than 99%, which was achieved
through the use of a secondary stripper foil (80 mu-
g/cm2 carbon) in advance of the HRIBF tandem
analyzing magnet to fully strip both the 10Be beam
and the 10B contaminant. This resulted in most of the
10B being removed from the beam.
